FBIS4-43399 "drweu116_n_94004" FBIS-WEU-94-116 Daily Report 22 May 1994 NORDIC COUNTRIES Finland Poll Shows Slight Improvement in Aho's Rating Poll Shows Slight Improvement in Aho's Rating 94P20880A Helsinki HELSINGIN SANOMAT in Finnish 22 May 94 p 10 94P20880A Helsinki HELSINGIN SANOMAT Finnish CSO [Finnish News Service report: "Over Half Dissatisfied With the Government"] [Text] Although the government led by Prime Minister Esko Aho (Center Party) has increased its popular support, a majority 53 percent of Finns are still dissatisfied with it. According to an opinion poll conducted by Gallup of Finland for the [Oulu] newspaper KALEVA, less than one-fifth of citizens, or 18 percent, are satisfied with the government, and of these, only 2 percent said they were extremely well satisfied. All told, the proportion of those satisfied with the government has risen by 4 percentage points since the December survey. One-fourth, or 26 percent, of those interviewed said they were extremely dissatisfied. Another full one-fourth refused to state an opinion as to whether they were satisfied or dissatisfied. The satisfaction of farmers with the government has risen by one-fifth since the previous poll. Of this occupational group, nearly half -- or 46 percent -- give the government a good grade. Aho's own personal performance was also rated as satisfactory by around one-fifth of citizens. The prime minister's approval rating has risen by 4 points since December.
